---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const mloBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Mortgage Loan Officer Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Mortgage loan officer mortgage from a lender who reads SAFE Act NMLS-registered W-2 depository commission, 1099 broker channel Schedule C, branch override income, S-corp top producer structure, and interest-rate-cycle production volatility as one income picture.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Working mortgage loan officers (MLOs) carry one of the most channel-specific qualifying profiles in sales. <strong>Per BLS OOH May 2024 data, all loan officers run a median wage of $79,910 with top 10% over $146,840. But these all-loan-officer numbers substantially understate working residential MLO compensation: established retail MLOs at depository banks (Wells Fargo, JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America, US Bank, Citi, regional banks) and IMB retail (loanDepot, Mr. Cooper, Rocket Mortgage retail) commonly earn $150K&ndash;$400K through W-2 base plus commission structure; top-producing broker channel MLOs at independent mortgage brokerages commonly $250K&ndash;$800K+ through Schedule C 1099 commission; branch managers $300K&ndash;$650K combining personal production with branch override income; and the top 1% of MLOs (the Scotsman Guide Top Originators list our principal broker Jim Blackburn has appeared on 7 times) earn $1M&ndash;$5M+ annually through high-volume production at $100M&ndash;$500M+ of annual closed loan volume</strong>. Income channels split sharply: depository retail produces W-2 with commission per-loan structure paid under CFPB Regulation Z Loan Originator Compensation Rule; broker channel produces 1099-NEC Schedule C commission through the brokerage entity with self-employment tax exposure; branch managers earn override at 5&ndash;25 basis points of branch volume on top of personal production. Income volatility is driven by interest-rate cycles &mdash; the 2020-2021 refi boom produced peak earnings, the 2022-2024 rate environment compressed production, and qualifying mechanics must reflect the 2-year average accurately. <strong>Critical contrast: MLOs are NOT eligible for Physician/Doctor Loan products (similar to realtors, pharmacists, vets) &mdash; the optimal path is properly-structured Conventional with channel-appropriate documentation: B3-3.1-01 W-2 + commission for depository MLOs, B3-3.3-02 Schedule C with Form 1084 addbacks for broker channel MLOs, and B3-3.4-02 S-corp + K-1 for top producers who have made the election.</strong></p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Schedule a call with Jim</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how MLO qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in MLO mortgages &mdash; Jim Blackburn is himself a 7&times; Scotsman Guide Top Producer who lives this profession every day and understands MLO qualifying because it&rsquo;s his own</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/5849563/pexels-photo-5849563.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Mortgage loan officer reviewing loan files at office desk" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=MLOs';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$150K-$800K+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Established working residential MLO income range across retail W-2 ($150K-$400K typical) and broker channel 1099 ($250K-$800K+ for top producers); top 1% Scotsman Guide originators $1M-$5M+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">50-150 bps</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Typical commission paid to MLO per closed loan (basis points on funded loan amount, varying by channel and tier; e.g., $400K loan at 100 bps = $4K commission)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">SAFE Act / NMLS</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Federal SAFE Act of 2008 requires all MLOs to register through NMLS (Nationwide Multistate Licensing System) and obtain state licensing with 20 hours pre-licensing education plus 8 hours continuing education annually</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">Reg Z LO Comp</div>
            <div class="stat-label">CFPB Regulation Z Loan Originator Compensation Rule (effective 2014) prohibits MLO compensation varying based on loan terms; allows variation based on loan amount (basis-points pricing)</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8867204/pexels-photo-8867204.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Mortgage loan officer with client" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=MLO';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies working mortgage loan officers on the full income picture &mdash; <strong>depository retail bank W-2 commission income under Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 as variable income with 24-month average plus base salary where applicable, IMB retail W-2 commission similar treatment, independent mortgage brokerage 1099-NEC Schedule C commission income through the wholesale broker channel under Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02 with 2-year averaging and Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks for non-cash deductions, branch manager override income paid on branch funded volume (typically 5-25 basis points of branch production), recruiting bonuses paid to branch and regional managers under B3-3.1-01, S-corp election structures for top-producing brokers combining W-2 reasonable compensation with K-1 distributions under B3-3.4-02 from Form 1120-S, wholesale lender employer W-2 for MLOs working at UWM, Rocket Pro TPO, Plaza Home Mortgage, or other wholesale lender account executive roles, Scotsman Guide Top Producer recognition supporting the high-tier income narrative for elite producers, AIME (Association of Independent Mortgage Experts) and MBA (Mortgage Bankers Association) industry context, and SAFE Act NMLS licensure documentation establishing professional credential</strong>. A new-licensed MLO building first book of business at retail bank or brokerage, an established retail MLO at depository, an established broker channel MLO at independent mortgage brokerage, a top-producing MLO at $100M+ annual volume, and a branch manager combining personal production with override each get qualified using methods that fit their actual structure. <strong>This page is written by an insider: our principal broker Jim Blackburn is himself a 7&times; Scotsman Guide Top Producer who has lived the depository-to-broker channel transition and built one of the top wholesale mortgage operations in Florida. The MLO mortgage qualifying mechanics on this page reflect that direct experience.</strong> Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other sales professional paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/sales-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">sales professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; MLO mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every mortgage loan officer should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Channel matters</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The depository retail vs broker channel distinction is the single biggest qualifying variable for MLOs. Retail MLOs receive W-2 commission income qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> as variable income with 24-month average. Broker channel MLOs receive 1099-NEC Schedule C commission qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 addbacks. The W-2 vs 1099 split changes every aspect of the documentation requirement.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">SAFE Act / NMLS</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The federal SAFE Act of 2008 (Secure and Fair Enforcement for Mortgage Licensing Act) requires all residential MLOs to register through the <a href="https://nationwidelicensingsystem.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Nationwide Multistate Licensing System (NMLS)</a> and obtain state licensing. NMLS ID stays with the individual MLO across employers. Public verification through <a href="https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NMLS Consumer Access</a>. We document the NMLS ID and employment history for underwriting context.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Reg Z LO Comp</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/36/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CFPB Regulation Z Loan Originator Compensation Rule</a> (effective 2014, codified at 12 CFR 1026.36) governs MLO compensation. Key rules: MLO comp cannot vary based on loan terms (rate, fees, type) but can vary based on loan amount; dual-compensation from creditor + consumer prohibited; steering of borrowers to specific loan products for personal gain prohibited.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Rate-cycle volatility</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">MLO production is highly interest-rate-sensitive. 2020-2021 refi boom produced peak income; 2022-2024 rate environment compressed production by 40-60%; 2025+ normalizing. The 2-year averaging window matters strategically &mdash; we evaluate whether the current 2-year average favors current close or anticipated rebound.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your MLO career</div>
        <h2>Mortgage loan officer mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each stage of an MLO career has its own qualifying logic. A new-licensed MLO at a retail bank in years 1-2 has a different mortgage path than an established broker channel MLO at $300K Schedule C income, or a top-producing MLO at $100M+ annual volume, or a branch manager combining personal production with branch override income.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">New-licensed MLO (Years 1&ndash;2)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Recently SAFE Act licensed and NMLS registered. Building first book of business at retail bank (Wells Fargo, Chase, Bank of America, US Bank, Citi, regional), IMB retail (loanDepot, Mr. Cooper), or independent brokerage. Limited 2-year history."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $60K&ndash;$110K W-2 base + ramping commission</li>
            <li>SAFE Act licensure + NMLS active status verified</li>
            <li>2-year history not yet established for sole qualifying</li>
            <li>Conventional with W-2 documentation + possible co-borrower</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See new-MLO mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established retail MLO (depository / IMB)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established W-2 MLO at depository bank or IMB retail with consistent 2-year production history. Base salary plus commission per closed loan typically 50-100 bps. Branch support and lead generation."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $150K&ndash;$400K W-2 base + commission</li>
            <li>2-year history supports full B3-3.1-01 variable income qualifying</li>
            <li>Commission typically 50-100 bps of funded volume</li>
            <li>Conventional Conforming or Jumbo with W-2 documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See retail MLO mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established broker channel MLO</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established 1099-NEC MLO at independent mortgage brokerage operating through wholesale lender channel (UWM, Rocket Pro TPO, ARIVE-platform lenders). Schedule C self-employment with higher commission tier (100-150+ bps net)."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $200K&ndash;$800K+ Schedule C 1099 commission</li>
            <li>Wholesale channel net commission typically 100-150+ bps</li>
            <li>B3-3.3-02 with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 addbacks</li>
            <li>Bank Statement Non-QM alternative for high-deduction MLOs</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See broker channel mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Top-producing MLO ($100M+ annual volume)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Top-producing MLO at $100M-$500M+ of annual closed loan volume. Often appears on Scotsman Guide Top Originators rankings. May have made S-corp election. Possibly building team of junior MLOs with override component."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $500K&ndash;$2M+ depending on volume + channel</li>
            <li>S-corp typical: W-2 reasonable comp + K-1 distributions</li>
            <li>Possible team override income on junior MLO production</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with B3-3.4-02 multi-source documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See top producer mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Branch manager / brokerage owner</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Branch manager at retail bank or IMB combining personal MLO production with branch override income on branch funded volume, OR independent brokerage owner combining personal Schedule C with brokerage entity K-1 distributions."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $300K&ndash;$1.5M+ across personal + override + entity</li>
            <li>Branch override typically 5-25 bps of branch funded volume</li>
            <li>Recruiting bonuses for branch growth</li>
            <li>Multi-source documentation under B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.4-02</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See manager / owner mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your MLO mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every MLO file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on your channel (depository W-2 vs broker channel 1099), your career stage, whether you operate as a branch manager with override income, and whether you have made the S-corp election as a top producer.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Depository / IMB retail W-2 + commission (the retail MLO default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for working retail MLOs at depository banks (Wells Fargo, JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America, US Bank, Citi, regional banks) and IMB retail employers (loanDepot, Mr. Cooper, Rocket Mortgage retail). Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, W-2 base salary plus commission income qualifies as variable income with 24-month average. Commission structure varies by employer but commonly runs 50-100 basis points of funded loan amount per closed loan, paid per CFPB Regulation Z LO Comp Rule constraints. Commission tier ladders may increase basis points at volume thresholds. Year-end production bonuses common at depository retail. The 24-month average smooths interest-rate-cycle commission volatility.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Broker channel Schedule C 1099 + Form 1084 addbacks (the broker channel default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for broker channel MLOs at independent mortgage brokerages operating through wholesale lender channels (United Wholesale Mortgage/UWM, Rocket Pro TPO, Plaza Home Mortgage, Homepoint historically, ARIVE-platform lenders). Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, Schedule C self-employment income qualifies with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks. Broker channel net commission typically runs 100-150+ basis points of funded volume due to lower brokerage overhead vs retail. Working broker channel MLOs take substantial Schedule C deductions for marketing, leads (Zillow, Bankrate, LendingTree, custom CRM/lead gen), office expenses, NMLS continuing education, professional dues (MBA, AIME), and technology subscriptions. Form 1084 systematically restores non-cash deductions for vehicle depreciation, home office, equipment depreciation, and amortization under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/167" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 167</a>.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; S-corp top producer election (top producer optimization)</h3>
      <p>For top-producing MLOs at $300K+ of annual Schedule C net income who have made S-corp election to optimize self-employment tax. Under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1361" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 1361</a> and <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, qualifying income combines S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $120K-$200K for MLO owner-operators) plus K-1 distributions from <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1120-s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1120-S</a> with 2-year history. Form 1084 addbacks at S-corp level recover non-cash deductions. MLO sales practice is generally NOT classified as SSTB under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> (mortgage origination is not health/law/accounting), potentially qualifying for the 20% QBI deduction subject to wage limitations at higher income.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Multi-source MLO (personal + branch override + recruiting bonus)</h3>
      <p>For branch managers and producing managers combining personal MLO production with branch override income on branch funded volume (typically 5-25 basis points of branch production) and recruiting bonuses for branch growth. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, all W-2 streams aggregate as continuing variable income with 24-month average. For branch managers structured as Schedule C contractors with override revenue, B3-3.3-02 applies similarly. Combined personal production + branch override + recruiting bonus commonly produces $400K-$1M+ for established branch managers at productive branches. Documentation includes branch funded volume reports, override calculation methodology, and recruiting bonus structures.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/8867204/pexels-photo-8867204.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on an MLO file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income facts that show up consistently on working MLO files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore, mis-categorize, or refuse to apply correctly. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to read the MLO channel-specific pattern properly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Channel-specific income classification (W-2 retail vs 1099 broker)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">The depository retail vs broker channel distinction is the single biggest qualifying variable for MLOs. Retail MLOs receive W-2 commission qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a> as variable income with 24-month average. Broker channel MLOs receive 1099-NEC Schedule C commission qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a> with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 addbacks. Generalist lenders sometimes apply B3-3.1-01 to a Schedule C 1099 broker channel MLO file (resulting in incorrect treatment) or fail to recognize the channel transition implications when an MLO has moved from retail to broker mid-period.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Per-loan basis-points commission structure (50-150+ bps)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">MLO commission per closed loan typically runs 50-100 basis points of funded loan amount at retail (depository / IMB retail) and 100-150+ basis points at broker channel. For an MLO funding $30M annually at 100 bps net, commission is $300K. For top producers at $100M+ volume with 100-150 bps, commission can reach $1M-$1.5M+. Under <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/36/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">CFPB Regulation Z Loan Originator Compensation Rule</a>, the basis-points structure must apply consistently to loan amount, not loan terms. Generalist underwriting often doesn&rsquo;t understand the basis-points commission structure or how production volume translates to income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Branch override income (5-25 bps of branch funded volume)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Branch managers earn override compensation on branch funded volume in addition to personal MLO production. Override typically runs 5-25 basis points of branch production depending on employer and branch tier. For a branch funding $200M annually at 15 bps override, branch override produces $300K of additional income on top of personal commission. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, branch override qualifies as continuing variable income with 24-month average. Generalist lenders often classify branch override as "management bonus not stable" or refuse to count it at all.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Interest-rate-cycle production volatility (refi vs purchase)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">MLO production is highly interest-rate-sensitive. The 2020-2021 refi boom produced peak income for many top MLOs (200-300% of normal-cycle income), while the 2022-2024 rate environment compressed production by 40-60% as refi disappeared and purchase market tightened. The 2-year B3-3.3-02 or B3-3.1-01 averaging window matters strategically &mdash; an MLO with 2021 record year + 2023 weak year produces a 2-year average that may not reflect current capacity. We evaluate whether current 2-year average favors close now or anticipated 2025+ rebound, and consider Bank Statement Program Non-QM as alternative documenting recent recovery deposits.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks for broker channel MLOs</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Working broker channel MLOs take substantial Schedule C deductions: lead generation costs (Zillow, Bankrate, LendingTree, custom marketing), CRM and technology subscriptions, vehicle depreciation, home office, NMLS continuing education, professional dues (<a href="https://www.aimegroup.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">AIME</a>, <a href="https://www.mba.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">MBA</a>), conference attendance, and brokerage operating expenses. Form 1084 systematically restores non-cash deductions under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a>. Generalist lenders may use Line 31 of Schedule C directly &mdash; missing $30K-$80K of addbacks that working MLOs routinely have.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Scotsman Guide Top Producer recognition + AIME credentialing</h3>
