  <!-- ============ H2 #6: INDUSTRY CONTEXT ============ -->
  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Why this mortgage requires specialty expertise</div>
        <h2>The MLO mortgage in context: 6 forces shaping how loan officers qualify.</h2>
        <p>MLO mortgage qualifying sits at the intersection of mortgage industry consolidation toward megalenders, the wholesale-vs-retail channel competitive dynamic, interest-rate-cycle income volatility, mortgage technology platform disruption, AIME advocacy and broker channel growth, and Scotsman Guide top producer industry tracking. Each force shapes what a working MLO&rsquo;s qualifying picture looks like.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Force 1 &mdash; Mortgage industry consolidation toward megalenders</h3>
      <p>The U.S. residential mortgage origination industry has consolidated substantially over the past decade. United Wholesale Mortgage (UWM, NYSE: UWMC), Rocket Companies (NYSE: RKT, parent of Rocket Mortgage), Pennymac Financial Services (NYSE: PFSI), Mr. Cooper Group, loanDepot, and Newrez/Caliber/Rithm have aggregated substantial origination market share. UWM in particular has become the largest U.S. mortgage originator by volume and the dominant wholesale lender in the broker channel. The mortgage implication for MLOs: employment opportunities split sharply between megalender retail W-2 positions and broker channel 1099 positions, with corresponding documentation differences.</p>

      <h3>Force 2 &mdash; Wholesale vs retail channel competitive dynamic</h3>
      <p>The wholesale broker channel (independent mortgage brokerages operating through wholesale lenders like UWM, Rocket Pro TPO, Plaza Home Mortgage) has grown substantially over the past decade as broker advocates (<a href="https://www.aimegroup.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AIME</a>) and UWM&rsquo;s anti-megalender retail positioning have pulled top producers from retail channel into independent brokerage. Broker channel net commission tier (100-150+ bps) typically exceeds retail commission tier (50-100 bps) due to lower brokerage overhead. The mortgage implication: MLOs moving from retail to broker channel mid-period create transition-year income documentation challenges that require careful B3-3.1-01 retail + B3-3.3-02 broker channel handling.</p>

      <h3>Force 3 &mdash; Interest-rate-cycle income volatility</h3>
      <p>MLO production is among the most interest-rate-sensitive income streams in any profession. The Federal Reserve Federal Funds Rate cycle drives mortgage rates that drive refi volume that drives MLO commission. The 2020-2021 cycle produced record refi volume (top MLOs at 200-300% of normal-cycle income); 2022-2024 produced rate-induced refi collapse with MLO production down 40-60%; 2025+ slowly normalizing as rates trend lower. The 2-year B3-3.3-02 / B3-3.1-01 averaging window matters &mdash; MLO mortgage timing relative to rate cycle position substantially affects qualifying capacity.</p>

      <h3>Force 4 &mdash; Mortgage technology platform disruption</h3>
      <p>Mortgage technology disruption from <a href="https://www.rocketmortgage.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Rocket Mortgage</a>, Better.com (NASDAQ: BETR), Blend (NYSE: BLND), and other tech-forward platforms has reshaped origination economics. Rocket Mortgage&rsquo;s integrated retail-direct model competes against broker channel through scale and technology. Better.com&rsquo;s direct-to-consumer model with reduced commission cost structure has affected MLO compensation pressure. The mortgage implication: MLO compensation structures continue evolving, with newer compensation models (salaried-LO with bonus, hybrid commission, base-plus-commission with reduced bps) emerging across employers.</p>

      <h3>Force 5 &mdash; AIME advocacy and wholesale broker channel growth</h3>
      <p><a href="https://www.aimegroup.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AIME (Association of Independent Mortgage Experts)</a> has been the leading trade association advocating for the wholesale broker channel since founding in 2018. AIME&rsquo;s Brokers United advocacy plus UWM&rsquo;s All-In wholesale-only initiative have substantially shifted top MLOs from retail to broker channel. Mortgage broker channel market share has grown materially &mdash; <a href="https://www.mba.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MBA (Mortgage Bankers Association)</a> tracks channel share data. The mortgage implication: increasing number of MLOs qualify under Schedule C 1099 broker channel mechanics rather than retail W-2.</p>

      <h3>Force 6 &mdash; Scotsman Guide top producer industry tracking</h3>
      <p>The Scotsman Guide Top Originators annual ranking tracks highest-producing residential MLOs by total dollar volume and units originated. Top producers appearing on the list (top 1% of U.S. MLOs by production) represent the elite tier earning $1M-$5M+ annually. <strong>Stairway Mortgage&rsquo;s principal broker Jim Blackburn has appeared on the Scotsman Guide Top Producer list 7 times, providing direct insider perspective on the elite MLO income tier that informs every mortgage qualifying conversation he leads.</strong> The mortgage implication: Scotsman Guide ranking provides supporting documentation for high-tier MLO income narrative.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

