        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a broker channel MLO at an independent brokerage. Does my Schedule C income qualify like a regular borrower?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; broker channel MLO Schedule C 1099 commission qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a> with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks. The qualifying mechanic is identical to any other Schedule C self-employed borrower, but the deduction patterns common to MLOs (leads, technology, NMLS CE, AIME/MBA dues, vehicle, home office) commonly produce significant Form 1084 addback opportunities. Done properly, working broker channel MLOs qualify on income levels their tax-return Line 31 alone doesn&rsquo;t reflect.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a retail MLO at Wells Fargo with W-2 + commission. How does qualifying work?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Retail MLO W-2 base salary plus commission qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> as variable income with 24-month average. Commission per closed loan (typically 50-100 bps of funded volume at retail) averages across the period to produce qualifying monthly income. Year-end production bonuses can qualify as continuing variable income with proper employer documentation of the production-based formula and multi-year continuity.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My 2021 income was much higher than 2023 due to the refi boom. How does the 2-year average treat that?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">The B3-3.3-02 or B3-3.1-01 2-year average smooths interest-rate-cycle volatility. For MLOs with strong 2021-2022 records but weaker 2023-2024 (the post-refi-boom transaction volume decline scenario), the 2-year average produces a number between the boom-year peak and the current adjusted level. Strategic timing matters: if rate-cycle position favors anticipated 2025+ rebound, alternative paths (Bank Statement Non-QM showing recent recovery deposits, Asset-Depletion Non-QM using boom-year liquid reserves) may produce stronger qualifying. We model the options.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a branch manager. How does my branch override income count for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Branch override income (typically 5-25 basis points of branch funded volume) qualifies as continuing variable income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> with 24-month average plus employer documentation of the override calculation methodology and multi-year continuity. For branch managers with established 2-year+ override history, this income aggregates fully with personal MLO commission and any recruiting bonuses. Generalist lenders often misclassify branch override as "management bonus not stable" &mdash; we document the production-based override structure properly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for an MLO mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically: two complete federal 1040s with all schedules including Schedule C if broker channel or self-employed; if S-corp top producer, Form 1120-S returns with K-1s; all W-2s including base, commission, override, recruiting bonus components if retail; all 1099-NECs from brokerage entity if broker channel; current SAFE Act licensure documentation; NMLS ID verification through NMLS Consumer Access; employer letter documenting commission and override calculation methodology with multi-year continuity; 60 days of personal and business bank statements.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I just transitioned from retail W-2 to broker channel 1099 9 months ago. How do I qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Channel transitions create documentation complexity. The recent 9 months of broker channel Schedule C history doesn&rsquo;t yet meet the B3-3.3-02 2-year requirement. Alternative paths: (1) extend documentation to include the prior retail W-2 history as continuing employment in the same profession, arguing for combined qualifying under B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.3-02 with continuity documentation; (2) Bank Statement Program Non-QM using 12 or 24 months of current broker channel bank statements; (3) wait until 2-year Schedule C history establishes (typically 21-24 months post-transition). We model the options.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My commission structure is "per loan" basis points. How does the underwriter understand this?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">CFPB <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/36/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Regulation Z Loan Originator Compensation Rule</a> (12 CFR 1026.36) governs MLO commission structures and is well-understood by experienced underwriters. The basis-points-per-loan structure (50-150 bps of funded loan amount, varying by channel and tier) produces commission income calculated as: funded volume &times; bps. We provide employer letter documenting the bps structure and 24-month funded volume history to support the variable income calculation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m on the Scotsman Guide Top Originators list. Does that help my qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly &mdash; Scotsman Guide ranking doesn&rsquo;t directly qualify income but supports the high-tier MLO income narrative for underwriting context. For top-producing MLOs at $1M+ annual income, the Scotsman Guide ranking provides industry-recognized documentation of production tier that helps underwriters contextualize the high income level. Our principal broker Jim Blackburn understands this well from his own 7&times; appearances on the list.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I make S-corp election for my MLO practice?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically at $300K+ of annual net Schedule C income for broker channel MLOs, S-corp election starts producing meaningful self-employment tax savings. S-corp election involves paying yourself W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $120K-$200K for MLO owner-operators) and taking remaining profit as K-1 distributions. Coordinate timing with your CPA. We model qualifying impact pre vs post S-corp election.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for MLOs since we&rsquo;re in the industry?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; mortgage rates for MLOs are the same as for any other borrower at the same credit profile, loan amount, and program selection. There&rsquo;s no industry penalty for MLO borrowers and no preferential treatment either. The qualifying mechanics are what determine outcome &mdash; not borrower industry. We work through standard pricing competitively.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My Schedule C income is suppressed by heavy lead generation and tech deductions. Can I still qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; this is exactly what Form 1084 cash-flow analysis under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> addresses. Vehicle depreciation, home office depreciation, equipment depreciation, and amortization items are non-cash deductions that Form 1084 systematically adds back. For working broker channel MLOs, Form 1084 commonly recovers $30K-$80K of qualifying income above Schedule C Line 31. Bank Statement Program Non-QM offers another path for severely-deduction-heavy MLOs where Form 1084 alone doesn&rsquo;t restore enough.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m planning to start my own mortgage brokerage. How does that fit with personal mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Sequencing matters. Personal mortgage close BEFORE brokerage startup uses established Schedule C MLO history (predictable qualifying). Personal mortgage close AFTER brokerage startup requires 2-year post-startup history of the new brokerage entity for full qualifying treatment. We typically recommend closing personal mortgage first, then pursuing brokerage startup 6-12 months later with the personal mortgage already secured.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also a sales professional (realtor). How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">MLO + realtor households produce strong joint qualifying when both spouses have established 2-year histories. Both files combine as co-borrowers with full B3-3.1-01 (MLO W-2 retail) or B3-3.3-02 (MLO broker channel or realtor) analysis on each profession. Combined household income from MLO + realtor commonly $300K-$900K supports $1M-$2M+ qualifying. Many MLO + realtor households also have rental investment portfolios adding Schedule E income under B3-3.1-08.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My commission was much higher in Q4 due to year-end push. Does that affect averaging?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Seasonal commission variation (Q4 push, spring purchase season for purchase-focused MLOs, refi waves during rate drops) is normal MLO production pattern. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> for W-2 or B3-3.3-02 for Schedule C, the 2-year average smooths seasonal variation. Single quarters don&rsquo;t dominate the qualifying calculation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders sometimes refuse MLO files?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Five reasons: (1) channel-specific income classification confusion (applying retail W-2 rules to broker channel Schedule C or vice versa); (2) branch override income classified as "management bonus not stable" rather than properly aggregated under B3-3.1-01; (3) recruiting bonuses treated as "discretionary" rather than continuing variable income; (4) interest-rate-cycle income volatility treated as "deteriorating earning capacity" rather than rate-cycle-driven; (5) Schedule C deductions reducing Line 31 without proper Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks. The income is all there and verifiable &mdash; the file just needs a broker who reads MLO multi-channel structure correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My recruiting bonuses for new MLO additions vary by quarter. Does that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Branch manager recruiting bonuses for adding new MLOs to the branch typically qualify under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> as variable income with 24-month average when documented through employer letter confirming the recruiting bonus structure and multi-year continuity. Quarterly variation smooths in the 2-year average. We coordinate with the branch operations director for proper documentation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically designed for MLOs?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No specialty MLO-specific products are widely available. What matters is finding a broker who understands MLO channel-specific qualifying mechanics: B3-3.1-01 retail W-2 + commission + override + bonus aggregation, B3-3.3-02 broker channel Schedule C with full Form 1084 addbacks, B3-3.4-02 S-corp top producer election, and the interest-rate-cycle context that shapes MLO income trajectory. We do this work natively because Jim is an MLO himself.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use bank statements alone instead of tax returns?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes through Bank Statement Program Non-QM products for broker channel MLOs whose Schedule C deductions suppress tax return income that Form 1084 addbacks can&rsquo;t fully restore. 12 or 24 months of business bank statements qualify under the Bank Statement Non-QM framework. Pricing carries 0.75-1.5% rate premium vs Conventional. Useful for high-deduction broker channel MLOs in transition between record years.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My SAFE Act licensure shows on NMLS Consumer Access. Will the underwriter verify it?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; underwriters routinely verify MLO licensure through <a href="https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NMLS Consumer Access</a>. Your NMLS ID, state licensing status, employment history, and any disciplinary actions are publicly visible. Active SAFE Act status with no compliance issues supports clean underwriting. We confirm NMLS active status at application time.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the IRS Section 199A QBI deduction affect me as a broker channel MLO?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Mortgage origination is generally NOT classified as SSTB under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> &mdash; the SSTB list covers health, law, accounting, financial services, and similar services that involve "performance of services" by the principal. Mortgage brokerage operations as product-distribution business may qualify for the full 20% QBI deduction subject to wage limitations at higher income. Coordinate with your CPA on documentation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a producing branch manager. My W-2 has multiple components. Does the underwriter understand that?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Multi-component MLO W-2 (base salary + personal commission + branch override + recruiting bonus + year-end production bonus) is the standard structure for branch managers. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, all components aggregate as continuing variable income with 24-month average. We provide employer letter from operations or HR documenting each component, the calculation methodology, and multi-year continuity. This is bread-and-butter MLO documentation when done by an MLO-focused broker.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My broker channel commission flows through the brokerage entity then to me. How is that documented?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Standard broker channel flow: wholesale lender pays the brokerage entity, brokerage retains its split, remainder distributed to MLO as 1099-NEC. Your Schedule C reflects the 1099-NEC commission received from the brokerage. We document this flow through the brokerage&rsquo;s commission disbursement records, your 1099-NEC, your Schedule C, and your personal 1040. The personal 1099-NEC numbers drive B3-3.3-02 qualifying calculation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My brokerage uses ARIVE / Encompass / Calyx for loan origination. Does the system matter for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; the loan origination system (LOS) your brokerage uses doesn&rsquo;t affect MLO income qualifying. What matters is the documented funded volume and commission income flowing to you regardless of the originating LOS. Your funded volume reports from the LOS support the 24-month production history documentation for B3-3.1-01 or B3-3.3-02.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 90-120 days before you intend to make an offer. MLO files benefit from runway because of channel-specific income classification, multi-component W-2 documentation for branch managers, full Form 1084 cash-flow analysis for broker channel MLOs, possible S-corp 1120-S review for top producers, and SAFE Act NMLS licensure verification. For MLOs in transition between retail and broker channel, additional runway helps establish the new-channel history that supports clean qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why does Stairway Mortgage understand MLO files better than other brokers?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Because our principal broker is an MLO. Jim Blackburn is a 7&times; Scotsman Guide Top Producer who has lived the depository-to-broker channel transition, built one of the top wholesale mortgage operations in Florida, and serves on AIME industry working groups. Every MLO mortgage qualifying conversation he leads reflects direct insider knowledge of how the income flows, what the cycle dynamics are, what the underwriting traps are, and how to structure the file for the actual income picture. We&rsquo;re MLOs serving MLOs.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

