        <p>Established broker channel MLO, 5 years post-SAFE Act licensure, working at an independent mortgage brokerage through UWM and Rocket Pro TPO. Schedule C gross commission income of $345K in 2023 (post-refi-boom adjustment year) and $285K in 2024 (continued rate-environment compression), 2-year average $315K gross. Net Schedule C after standard deductions: $215K in 2023 and $175K in 2024 (substantial lead generation costs through Zillow, Bankrate, LendingTree, and custom CRM; technology subscriptions for LOS, marketing automation, and CRM; NMLS continuing education; AIME and MBA dues; vehicle for client meetings; home office space). 2-year average net: $195K. SAFE Act licensure active and verified through NMLS Consumer Access with clean compliance history. The first lender pulled Schedule C Line 31 of $195K average directly without running Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks, treated the 2024 income decline as "deteriorating earning capacity rather than continuing income," didn&rsquo;t recognize the interest-rate-cycle context as the production driver, didn&rsquo;t document the broker channel commission structure properly through the wholesale lender flow (UWM and Rocket Pro TPO), and offered the MLO $485K Conventional. They missed that the B3-3.3-02 framework specifically requires Form 1084 cash-flow analysis to recover non-cash deductions for vehicle depreciation, home office, equipment depreciation, and amortization, which for working broker channel MLOs commonly produces $25K-$60K of recoverable addbacks. We pulled the personal 1040 with full Schedule C, the 1099-NECs from the brokerage entity confirming the wholesale commission flow, the NMLS Consumer Access verification showing active SAFE Act licensure with clean compliance, the funded volume reports from the LOS showing 24-month production history, and the brokerage&rsquo;s commission disbursement methodology under CFPB Reg Z LO Comp Rule compliance. Ran full Form 1084 cash-flow analysis under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">B3-3.3-02</a> recovering $34K of addbacks across 2 years for vehicle depreciation, home office, equipment depreciation, and amortization. Properly contextualized the 2024 production decline as interest-rate-cycle related (not capacity decline) through industry data showing the broader broker channel volume compression. Adjusted 2-year average qualifying income: $228K. Approved at $785K Conventional Jumbo for a Plantation home with dedicated home office space for the brokerage practice. Closed in 38 days. Form 1084 addback discipline plus rate-cycle context plus channel-specific documentation is the central qualifying lever for working broker channel MLOs &mdash; the first lender just didn&rsquo;t do the work. Our principal broker Jim Blackburn understands this directly because he&rsquo;s lived it: 7&times; Scotsman Guide Top Producer, built one of the top wholesale operations in Florida, knows the broker channel from the inside.</p>
